06211nam a22007575i 9780822374763DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20152016ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015026284  a97808223747637 a10.1515/97808223747632doi  a(DE-B1597)553404  a(OCoLC)1224279082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aPS3554.I259bZ75 2016 4aPS3554.I259bZ75 2016 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a813.600aJunot Díaz and the Decolonial Imagination /cMonica Hanna, José David Saldívar, Jennifer Harford Vargas. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Junot Díaz and the Decolonial Imagination From Island to Empire -- tPart I. Activist Aesthetics -- t1. Against the "Discursive Latino" -- t2. The Decolonizer's Guide to Disability -- t3. Laughing through a Broken Mouth in The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao -- t4. A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Cannibalist -- tPart II. Mapping Literary Geographies -- t5. Artistry, Ancestry, and Americanness in the Works of Junot Díaz -- t6. This Is How You Lose It -- t7. Latino/a Deracination and the New Latin American Novel -- t8. Dictating a Zafa -- tPart III. Doing Race in Spanglish -- t9. Dismantling the Master's House -- t10. Now Check It -- t11. A Planetary Warning? -- tPart IV. Desiring Decolonization -- t12. Junot Díaz's Search for Decolonial Aesthetics and Love -- t13. Sucia Love -- t14. "Chiste Apocalyptus" -- t15. The Search for Decolonial Love -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first sustained critical examination of the work of Dominican-American writer Junot Díaz, this interdisciplinary collection considers how Díaz's writing illuminates the world of Latino cultural expression and trans-American and diasporic literary history. Interested in conceptualizing Díaz's decolonial imagination and his radically re-envisioned world, the contributors show how his aesthetic and activist practice reflect a significant shift in American letters toward a hemispheric and planetary culture. They examine the intersections of race, Afro-Latinidad, gender, sexuality, disability, poverty, and power in Díaz's work. Essays in the volume explore issues of narration, language, and humor in The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao, the racialized constructions of gender and sexuality in Drown and This Is How You Lose Her, and the role of the zombie in the short story "Monstro." Collectively, they situate Díaz's writing in relation to American and Latin American literary practices and reveal the author's activist investments. The volume concludes with Paula Moya's interview with Díaz.Contributors: Glenda R. Carpio, Arlene Dávila, Lyn Di Iorio, Junot Díaz, Monica Hanna, Jennifer Harford Vargas, Ylce Irizarry, Claudia Milian, Julie Avril Minich, Paula M. L. Moya, Sarah Quesada, José David Saldívar, Ramón Saldívar, Silvio Torres-Saillant, Deborah R. Vargas  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDecolonization in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh1 aDávila, Arlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilian, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVargas, Deborah R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpio, Glenda R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Monica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarford Vargas, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVargas, Jennifer Har